#1 Status-post resection of a T4, N1 (1 of 51) sigmoid adenocarcinoma with direct invasion into the bladder and perforation, with residual microscopic disease left near radial margin
Mrs. Mann is a pleasant 64 year-old female from Tennessee with a resected perforated sigmoid cancer with invasion into the bladder.
Basic cancer education has been provided to the patient at the request of Dr. Lee Guyer's Service.  I have had the opportunity to review the operative report, surgical pathology, laboratory values, and notes in Documents Browser.  I have reviewed these findings with the patient and answered questions.  I have discussed this case in detail with Dr. Janie Wilhelm, my collaborating physician, who has guided my plan.
We have discussed the characteristics of the cancer, including the type of malignancy, size, grade, lymph node status, and stage of the cancer.
We would recommend chemotherapy in this situation.  Mrs. Mann will return in the outpatient seeing to discuss treatment recommendations.  At that time she will undergo a baseline CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis, comprehensive laboratory panel including a CEA, a chest x-ray, and a postoperative operation with Dr. Guyer.  She has verbalized understanding and is agreeable to the plan.   I have emphasized to her that she is to make contact with a local medical oncologist to help insure continuity of care and also set herself up with a primary-care provider.  She has verbalized understanding and is agreeable.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

[end section id="20112"]

